<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="382" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,639,952]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">
The species 
<taxonomicName authority="Hibisci Fabricius 1775" authorityName="Hibisci Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" box="[296,658,639,664]" class="Insecta" family="Bombycidae" genus="Bombyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[296,478,639,664]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Bombyx Hibisci</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[488,658,639,664]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" refId="ref3235" refString="Fabricius, J. Ch. (1775) Systema entomologiae: sistens insectorvm classes, ordines, genera, species, adiectis synonymis, locis, descriptionibvs, observationibvs. In Officina Libraria Kortii, Flensbvrgi et Lipsiae, 832 pp." type="book">Fabricius 1775</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
was described from an unspecified number of moths in the “Mus. Tottianum” (
<figureCitation box="[295,363,676,701]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1213,1236]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,1007,1189]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[150,1436,1007,1189]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. Original descriptions of taxa by Fabricius. 1. Bombyx hibisci; 2. B. orientalis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1439628/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Otto Thott was the Count in the Danish Government, and Fabricius used his entomological collection to describe several dozen new species with a remark “Mus. Tottianum” (
<bibRefCitation box="[1105,1267,711,736]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" refId="ref3497" refString="Zimsen, E. (1964) The type material of I. C. Fabricius. Munksgaard, Copenhagen, 656 pp." type="book">Zimsen, 1964</bibRefCitation>
). After Thott’s death in 1785 his collection was sold by auction, and a part was obtained by William Hunter (
<collectingRegion box="[1267,1370,748,773]" country="United Kingdom" name="Glasgow City" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Glasgow</collectingRegion>
) who bequeathed it to the University of 
<collectingRegion box="[557,658,783,808]" country="United Kingdom" name="Glasgow City" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Glasgow</collectingRegion>
. Thus, in 1807 the Hunterian Museum (and Art Gallery) was first opened, and is now the oldest museum in 
<collectingCountry box="[623,725,820,845]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Scotland</collectingCountry>
. A part of Fabricius’ entomological collection with his original labels is presented here today. The collection is available now digitally under The Hunterian online catalogue (https://www.gla.ac.uk/hunterian/collections/searchourcollections/#d.en. 
<date box="[961,1046,892,917]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" value="54-06-19">190654</date>
and http://collections.gla.ac.uk/ #view=list&amp;id=cb15&amp;keywords= 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" box="[531,609,927,952]" class="Insecta" family="Bombycidae" genus="Bombyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hibisci">hibisci</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,1106,1213,1236]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1439628/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" startId="1.[151,264,1213,1236]" targetBox="[150,1436,1007,1189]" targetPageId="1">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1106,1213,1236]" box="[151,1106,1213,1236]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,314,1213,1236]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">FIGURES 1–2.</emphasis>
Original descriptions of taxa by Fabricius. 1. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" box="[779,935,1213,1235]" class="Insecta" family="Bombycidae" genus="Bombyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hibisci">
<emphasis box="[779,935,1213,1235]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Bombyx hibisci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 2. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1793" box="[973,1101,1213,1236]" class="Insecta" family="Bombycidae" genus="Bombyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orientalis">B. orientalis</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1275,1804]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">
Two specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" box="[418,593,1275,1300]" class="Insecta" family="Bombycidae" genus="Bombyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hibisci">
<emphasis box="[418,593,1275,1300]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Bombyx hibisci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were thus discovered (
<figureCitation box="[862,968,1275,1300]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1951,1974]" captionTargetBox="[155,1432,1052,1925]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[150,1436,1047,1931]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 3–6. Type specimens of Eupterote ssp. described by Fabricius, adults and their labels. 3. Bombyx hibisci, ♂ lectotype (HMAG); 4. B. hibisci, ♂ paralectotype (HMAG); 5. Bombyx orientalis, ♂ lectotype (ZMKU/ZMUC); 6. The same, inventory label enlarged." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1439630/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Figs 3, 4</figureCitation>
), and they perfectly fit with the original description, which translates as ‘yellow with two dark fasciae on the forewing, the postmedia shortened; [there is] a single fascia on the hindwing’.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1275,1804]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">
The better preserved male of the species is designated here as the 
<typeStatus box="[939,1042,1382,1407]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">lectotype</typeStatus>
of this taxon. It bears an inventory number “133658” and a bottom label with ink inscription by Fabricius’ hand: “Bom. Hibisci | Fabr. P. 177. №45” (with double black frame). It will be supplied with a standard red rectangular label with corresponding printed text.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1275,1804]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">
The species is attributed to the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Hubner, 1820" authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1820" box="[651,933,1491,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Eupterotidae" genus="Eupterote" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[651,760,1492,1515]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Eupterote</emphasis>
Hübner, 1820
</taxonomicName>
, and the following combination (originally established by 
<bibRefCitation box="[331,540,1526,1551]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" refId="ref3204" refString="Aurivillius, Ch. (1897) Bemerkungen zu den von J. Chr. Fabricius aus Danischen Sammlungen beschriebenen Lepidopteren. Entomologisk tidskrift, 18, 139 - 170." type="journal article">Aurivillius (1897)</bibRefCitation>
but for another species!—see below) is here confirmed, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Fabricius, 1775)" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" class="Insecta" family="Eupterotidae" genus="Eupterote" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hibisci">
<emphasis box="[1238,1436,1526,1551]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Eupterote hibisci</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation box="[158,338,1563,1588]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" refId="ref3235" refString="Fabricius, J. Ch. (1775) Systema entomologiae: sistens insectorvm classes, ordines, genera, species, adiectis synonymis, locis, descriptionibvs, observationibvs. In Officina Libraria Kortii, Flensbvrgi et Lipsiae, 832 pp." type="book">Fabricius, 1775</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1275,1804]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">
It is likely that 
<taxonomicName authority="Moore, 1883" authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1883" box="[372,750,1598,1623]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Horanpella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="placida">
<emphasis box="[372,593,1598,1623]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Horanpella placida</emphasis>
Moore, 1883
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[762,1065,1598,1623]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">
The 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" authorityYear="1758" box="[812,949,1598,1623]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Lepidoptera</taxonomicName>
of 
<collectingCountry box="[986,1065,1598,1623]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Ceylon</collectingCountry>
</emphasis>
2: 143, pl. 137, fig. 1, described after females from 
<collectingCountry box="[364,448,1635,1660]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Ceylon</collectingCountry>
, is conspecific; however, males are necessary to address this problem.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1275,1804]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">
<bibRefCitation box="[199,403,1670,1695]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" refId="ref3204" refString="Aurivillius, Ch. (1897) Bemerkungen zu den von J. Chr. Fabricius aus Danischen Sammlungen beschriebenen Lepidopteren. Entomologisk tidskrift, 18, 139 - 170." type="journal article">Aurivillius (1897)</bibRefCitation>
who worked in 
<date box="[591,713,1671,1695]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" value="1892" valueMax="1894">1892-1894</date>
with Fabricius’ collection in Copenhagen, wrongly identified a male of 
<taxonomicName authority="Fabricius" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1793" box="[248,502,1707,1732]" class="Insecta" family="Bombycidae" genus="Bombyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orientalis">
<emphasis box="[248,389,1707,1732]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">B. orientalis</emphasis>
Fabricius
</taxonomicName>
from the 
<collectionCode box="[620,701,1707,1731]" country="Denmark" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/mci8-ehqk" name="Zoological Museum, University of Copenhagen" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">ZMUC</collectionCode>
as a 
<typeStatus box="[765,813,1708,1732]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">type</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[856,965,1707,1732]" class="Insecta" family="Eupterotidae" genus="Eupterote" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hibisci">
<emphasis box="[856,965,1707,1732]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">B. hibisci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Thus, he wrongly established a specific synonymy between 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[376,483,1742,1767]" class="Insecta" family="Eupterotidae" genus="Eupterote" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hibisci">
<emphasis box="[376,483,1742,1767]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">B. hibisci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Walker, 1855)" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1855" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1855" box="[538,853,1742,1767]" class="Insecta" family="Eupterotidae" genus="Eupterote" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="geminata">
<emphasis box="[538,674,1744,1767]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">E. geminata</emphasis>
(Walker, 1855)
</taxonomicName>
; however, these species are not closely related. It is likely that Aurivillius had not seen a 
<typeStatus box="[565,613,1780,1804]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">type</typeStatus>
specimen of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[764,870,1779,1804]" class="Insecta" family="Eupterotidae" genus="Eupterote" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hibisci">
<emphasis box="[764,870,1779,1804]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">B. hibisci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
